</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="preliminary conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Preliminary conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tobar &amp; M. F. Lopez" authorityYear="2021" class="Aves" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lepanthes oro-lojaensis" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oro-lojaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Lepanthes oro-lojaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is known only from the type location, and only two mature individuals were observed. After its discovery in 2015, two additional visits were conducted to explore surrounding areas but it was not possible to find more plants. However, it was evident that the original habitat is under strong pressure due to cattle ranching, the collection of remaining shrubs as firewood and a rapid transformation and fragmentation of the surrounding landscape due to fires and exotic species plantations such as 
<taxonomicName class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus radiata" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="radiata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Pinus radiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
D.Don (
<bibRefCitation author="Penafiel, M" editor="Fernandez-Fernadez, D" journalOrPublisher="GADPEO-INABIO, Quito" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="27 - 46" refId="B17" refString="Penafiel, M, Fernandez-Fernadez, D, Freire, E, Tobar, F, Munoz-Yanez, M, 2018. Introduccion. In: Fernandez-Fernadez, D, Garzon-Santomaro, C, Munoz-Yanez, M, Gonzales, D, Mena-Jaen, JL, Eds., ORQUIDEAS Y BROMELIAS DE LA PROVINCIA DE EL ORO: Una guia de identificacion para los principales generos y especies del paramo al manglar. GADPEO-INABIO, Quito: 27 - 46" title="Introduccion." volumeTitle="ORQUIDEAS Y BROMELIAS DE LA PROVINCIA DE EL ORO: Una guia de identificacion para los principales generos y especies del paramo al manglar." year="2018">Penafiel et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). Therefore, its small population size, area of occupancy of four km2, as well as its habitat restriction and degradation of its unique location allow us to apply criteria B of the 
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="University of Goeteborg, Stockholm" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" publicationUrl="https://portals.iucn.org/library/node/10315" refId="B8" refString="IUCN, 2012. IUCN red list categories and criteria: Version 3.1. Second edition. IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge. https://portals.iucn.org/library/node/10315" title="IUCN red list categories and criteria: Version 3.1. Second edition. IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge." url="https://portals.iucn.org/library/node/10315" year="2012">IUCN (2012)</bibRefCitation>
Red List. The species is preliminarily assessed as Critically Endangered (CR) B2a+b(ii,iii,v) given that it is known from a single location where its area of occupancy, habitat quality, and number of mature individuals are probably declining.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
Morphologically, the most similar species is 
<taxonomicName class="Aves" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lepanthes jimburae" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jimburae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Lepanthes jimburae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Comparison with the most similar species to Lepanthes oro-lojaensis Tobar &amp; M. F. Lopez A Lepanthes oro-lojaensis B Lepanthes jimburae C Lepanthes corkyae D Lepanthes schizix. Photographs by F. Tobar." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.180.62671.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/574519" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3b</figureCitation>
) from the southeastern slopes of the Ecuadorian Andes. From that species, 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. oro-lojaensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="oro-lojaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. oro-lojaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in the smaller plants, the dorsal sepal attenuate into a shorter decurved cauda, the lateral sepals with minutely denticulate margins and petals with the upper lobe ovate, with rounded apex and lower lobe triangular-oblong. The new species is also similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. corkyae" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="corkyae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. corkyae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Comparison with the most similar species to Lepanthes oro-lojaensis Tobar &amp; M. F. Lopez A Lepanthes oro-lojaensis B Lepanthes jimburae C Lepanthes corkyae D Lepanthes schizix. Photographs by F. Tobar." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.180.62671.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/574519" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3c</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. schizix" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="schizix">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. schizix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Comparison with the most similar species to Lepanthes oro-lojaensis Tobar &amp; M. F. Lopez A Lepanthes oro-lojaensis B Lepanthes jimburae C Lepanthes corkyae D Lepanthes schizix. Photographs by F. Tobar." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.180.62671.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/574519" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">3d</figureCitation>
), both occurring on the western slopes of the northern Ecuador and from which it differs in the red to reddish with yellow dorsal sepals, yellow lateral sepals suffused with red around the mid-vein (vs. orange to red brown sepals in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. corkyae" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="corkyae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. corkyae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and purple flower in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
L 
<taxonomicName class="Aves" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lepanthes schizix" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schizix">Lepanthes schizix</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
), lateral sepals in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. oro-lojaensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="oro-lojaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. oro-lojaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are minutely denticulate in the margin, are no denticulate in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. corkyae" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="corkyae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. corkyae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and minutely ciliate in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. schizix" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="schizix">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. schizix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In Both 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. corkyae" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="corkyae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. corkyae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. schizix" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="schizix">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. schizix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the lip blade are glabrous (vs. microscopically pubescent 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. oro-lojaensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="oro-lojaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. oro-lojaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and, lip blades are oblong in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. corkyae" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="corkyae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. corkyae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. oro-lojaensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="oro-lojaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. oro-lojaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and lunate in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. schizix" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="schizix">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. schizix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
